Halve, peel and finely chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Chop into small pieces. Trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed) then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces. Trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed) (no need to peel) then coarsely grate.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{1%splash} in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the shallot, pepper and courgette and cook, stirring, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g}, @vegetable stock powder{1/2} and @ground turmeric{1}.

Pour the @water{300%ml} into the pan and bring to the boil. Once boiling, lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on the pan. Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat. Remove the lid and quickly add the carrot (don't stir) then replace the lid and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

> The rice will finish cooking in its own steam.

Meanwhile, preheat your #grill{} to high and line a #baking tray{} with #foil{}. Zest the @lemon{1/2}(zested and cut into wedges) then chop into wedges. Halve the @red chilli{1/2}(halved, deseeded and finely chopped) lengthways, deseed and finely chop. Pop the @coley fillets{2} onto the prepared baking tray. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and sprinkle over the lemon zest. Drizzle with @olive oil{1%drizzle} then rub the flavourings all over the fish.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Have a clear down then pop the coley under the grill and cook for ~{6-8%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the centre.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and season to taste with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{} and a squeeze of lemon juice. Stir through the @flaked almonds{15%g}. Serve on plates topped with the grilled coley, a dollop of @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} and a sprinkling of chilli for those who want some kick. Serve any remaining lemon wedges on the side for squeezing over. Enjoy!